Recently started needing a place to store end-mils so I designed this box. It was also a chance to test dual extrusion with the new MakerWare 2.0. NOTE: if you go for dualstrusion you will need the font from: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:22730

The OpenSCAD is customizable for the size of your endmils, how many rows of end mills you want, how many end mills per row, spacing, height, etc. To lighten the load I print with 2 shells at 5% fill. Less plastic for the fill I believe helps prevent warping and layer separation on something with long runs like this. A 3x8 box like this takes almost six hours to print for the top and bottom each. You need to generate the files by uncommenting each three lines for each part at the end of the file: Specifically:
top();
box_top_label();
bottom(); You will likely want to set the label to be something besides "Scanner's end mills".
You can also comment out the place where the label is drawn in 'top()' and not worry about dualstrusion. NOTE: This uses the font from: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:22730 -- you can simply comment out the 'use' statement for this font and comment out the calls to 'labe()' in the openscad code to skip this. This is also maintained on github at: https://github.com/scanner/end_mill_box

This is a project to make a custom spool winder that you can put on a standard 5/16 threaded rod connected to a drill for winding your own filament onto a Robox reel. This fits the original reel and clicky's reel from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:547553 (assuming you scaled it correctly according to his directions). We're up to VERSION 6! This version features a a shorter skirt on the spool (no need for longer one), better bolt sizing, a little extra material in bolt area to permanently hold the nut, and finally a bit better sizing all around. I also included an alternate version of the backplate for those wishing to save a little filament. Your choice - solid or two options with holes. (4 large -alt1 - or 8 smaller - alt2) I imagine (since my printer is down) you have a trade off on print time vs. filament use from solid being the fastest to 8 holes being the least amount of filament. Take into count for those that asked for the holes - you may need more infill on ones with holes. This print requires the use of 3 nuts, one threaded rod and a drill. I made it originally measured for 5/16 (can you tell I'm American?) I believe this is close to the M8. You can tap the nut in with a hammer to make it near permanent. Final Note - This is a work in progress and at the moment my printer is down! Updates will come based on user feedback for now.

This is for clipping your HBP cables to the platform to prevent the wires from shifting and shorting.  I had an error where my bot would stop a few layers into a print.  While the layer was always random, the hot end was in roughly the same position each time - I finally (with some help from the makerbot google group) figured out it might be the HBP cables shorting when its in that particular position.
I kind of mashed up my idea with the self-leveling HBP idea someone else posted about a month ago...
I haven't mounted the HBP and printed with it yet after making this modification - so YMMV.  I anticipate there might be issues with it smacking into the bot housing at the Y- / Y+ extreme.

Unmount HBP.  I had to print on the default acrylic bed, because of the above issues.  Had minor warping and space issues - try rotating it about 30 degrees to print - this will make for a huge raft but the whole object will fit on the platform without head crashes.
I haven't printed this raftlessly, but it should do fine.
Unscrew your HBP from the build platform, leaving the M3 screws and nuts on the wood platform.  Unscrew the two screws nearest the HBP's connector area and screw this object down flat to the wood.
Thread a new M3 nut on each screw.  Tighten them all the way on the screws where this object is screwed to the build platform, and eyeball them on the other screws to make them roughly level.  The gap should be roughly 1mm on the other four screws.  Place the build platform in the machine with the HBP on top and adjust the nuts until level.  Place another nut on top of each screw and tighten against the previous nut.
Now use a cable tie or nylon zip-tie to firmly affix the cables to the back of the run.  I accomplished this by routing them in an X shape, applying kapton, then zip-tying them.  I plan to add a slot in the future to allow the wires to directly zip tie to the platform.

I've seen another design by emmett for a horizontal spool holder that fits on to the Z-bars of the PrintrBot but I found that the friction on the spool was a little too great and gave artefacts on the print when the filament was being pulled. I think that mounting the spool horizontally gives a very neat and stable design so I produced my own one that contains a built-in bearing to minimise friction (okay describing it as "zero friction" may be somewhat of an exaggeration). I guess I could have used real ball bearings here but picking up some marbles from a visit to the local toy shop seemed more in the DIY spirit of 3D printing. The result is a super-smooth action.. really, you should try it! I'm also rather pleased with the threaded spool retainer. Not only is this the first thread I've printed (and it works really well) but the conical design allows me to fit all the spool sizes that I've come across so far without any "wobble" (see photos). Obviously, don't tighten the knurled top too much or you'll lose the "zero-friction" action. The spool holder was designed in Moi3D which is a great (although paid) CSG modeller. For those of you who have, or want to try, Moi3D I've included the 3DM file here.

Print all three sections, Main, Upper and Top. I have printed these in ABS and PLA (the photos show PLA) at 0.3mm layer height and Support is not needed.  
Assemble by fitting the main section onto the PrintrBot bars with the filament guide coming out to the front and left. Load up the bearing with (in my case) eleven 16mm marbles and drop on the Upper bearing cover with the cone facing upward. Mount your spool on top - the filament must unwind anticlockwise as seen from above or the screw will tighten and eventually lock up the movement. Screw on the top piece and leave barely tight to allow the spool to rotate freely.  
Let me know how it goes.

remixed_from.title: P3Steel - Prusa i3 3mm Steel Laser cut (aka Leonardo)

description.text:
This is the same 3mm steel structure as the original P3Steel "Leonardo" by Irobri, version 2.0, with a few small changes listed below. This is why I am bumping the version to 2.01. There are no other changes apart from those listed below:

  • The interference between the Y stepper and the M3 nyloc nut holding the Y stepper support has been solved by stretching the support by 2mm.

  • The frame has been stretched by 9mm, meaning the Y-axis 8mm smooth rods should now be 350mm long (same as the original Prusa i3), and not 341mm long anymore (4mm have been added to the front and 5mm to the back).

  • Two 3mm holes have been added along the sides of the front Y-axis subframe, one on each side.

  • The almost useless part that could eventually be used as a Y belt holder has been deleted (there are much better designs that can simply be printed).
    • There are no other changes because imho the original P3Steel design is already practically perfect. Thank you Irobri for this awesome, superbly engineered Prusa i3 variant! Naturally I am releasing this modified design under the same license as the original. More information including BOM and assembly guide: http://reprap.org/wiki/P3Steel Este diseño de la P3Steel 2.01 es exactamente el mismo que la versión 2.0 a excepción de los cambios enumerados a continuación:
  • La interferencia entre el motor del eje Y y la tuerca nyloc M3 que sostiene el soporte del motor, ha sido resuelta por el estiramiento del soporte por 2 mm.
  • La estructura se ha estirado por 9 mm, es decir, el eje Y ahora necesita varillas lisas de 8 mm de 350 mm de largo (igual que la Prusa i3), y no más 341mm de largo (4 mm se han añadido a la parte frontal y 5 mm en la parte posterior).
  • Dos agujeros de 3 mm se han añadido a la parte delantera de la subtrama del eje Y, uno a cada lado.
  • La pieza de acero inútil que eventualmente podría ser utilizada como Y axis belt holder ha sido eliminada (hay mucho mejores diseños que simplemente se pueden imprimir, ver aqui en Thingiverse).
    • Agradezco a Irobri por su diseño genial de la P3Steel.

The frame for all P3Steel variants is designed to be laser cut from 3mm structural or stainless steel.  
BOM and detailed, illustrated assembly instructions can be found in the reprap.org wiki.

Hi Aurelio,
I changed as little as possible with the original design version 2.0 by Irobri because in my opinion there was little to improve on an almost perfect design, and any significant changes would have resulted in a heavier, less compact and more expensive to laser cut frame, hence detracting from some of the desirable qualities achieved by the original design.
You'll notice stretching the frame from 341mm to 350mm resulted in minimal increases in the total amount of steel used and in the length of the laser cutter tool path, so that was an "acceptable" improvement to me and it gives P3Steel builders a little bit more flexibility along the Y-axis to achieve the largest possible print volume (within the limits of the heated bed, of course).
The two holes you refer to, are for two M3 screws possibly used to attach optional accessories or wire guides. Compare the front part of the left and right gussets with Irobri's original parts and you'll find them easily. In my case I plan to use them to attach a pair of flexible USB LED lights.
As you can see all the small changes I made to the original design by Irobri have a purpose and their number and scope are strictly limited.
Regarding the P3SteelMM from Moebyus Machines, I don't see it as much of an improvement over Irobri's original version 2.0, for various reasons, but that is just my personal opinion.

This was a project to produce a number of Cookie Stamps for my wife's cutout cookies.

This is the process I used to create items such as this Cookie Stamp. I wanted to use Graphtec's Silhouette Studio to design my stamps because it offers an excellent tracing mechanism and ability to wrap text along a path such as a circle. I also wanted to use Autodesk 123Design to import an SVG file as a sketch and then extrude the sketch into a 3D object which could be exported as an STL file. I should mention I have a MAC Mini and would like to be able to use it exclusivly, but I also have various flavors of Windows Operating systems running on it as virtual PC's in Parallels Desktop. What seemed so simple turned out to be quite complicated for reasons I will explain. Silhouette Studio, it turns out will not let you export SVG files with the latest version, so you need an older Version like Version 1.9 to accomplish this. You also must use the premium paid version of Silhouette Studio Designer Edition in order for it to work. There are articles on the internet showing how to run both versions of Silhouette Studio for those who want to use all the latest features that version 3 provides. While AutoDesk 123Design is available (free) for MAC and PC, the MAC version does not properly import SVG files containing text. However, the PC version does work with no issues. The problem with that is that my PC is a virtual PC and Autodesk 123Design runs very slowly and is next to impossible to work on in the virtual environment. I am using Windows 8.1 as my virtual PC. So given the above issues, here is how I go about making a 3D STL file using the above tools. Open Silhouette Studio Designer Version 1.9 on the PC and create a new project. Create your design using the tracing tools, whatever. Save the file changing the extension from .studio to .svg Import the SVG file into AutoDesk 123Desgin (PC version). Save it as a 123 file. Now you can open the 123 File on the MAC and complete extruding the components and exporting the resulting project to an STL file. When creating a cookie stamp, the text must be reversed or mirrored in order to be viewed properly when used to stamp a cookie. Silhouette Studio allows you to mirror the text and place it on a path. Be careful when forcing it to a path. I created a circle as a path. Pulling the text to the circle sometimes places it on the inside rather than the outside of the circle. Using a bigger circle sometimes helps and then you can resize the circle after placing the text. For the handle on the cookie stamp, I placed a cyclinder on the grid of Autodesk 123Desgin and then placed a sphere on top of it. Pulling ths sphere down till it was half way thru to the cylinder produced the handle I then exported as an STL file. I glue the handle to the cookie stamp using PVC cement. I also made a few versions of the handle by modifying it in AutoDesk MeshMixer. This has been a learning experience. Took me two days to sort out all of the issues, but I can now easily create Cookie Stamps in any flavor I like. Some have a picture of a glass on them, others have different sayings. Oh, by the way, I scale the STL file to 35% before printing. You can scale it to suit the size cookie you wish to make.
Hope you can benefit from my experience.

There are many filament spools on Thingiverse already.  But when I didn't find one that was 100% printable, I couldn't resist the urge to design my own.  This is my first design so please be gentle.
I started with thingiverse.com/thing:4337 but I had trouble getting a good print, and the bearing rollers (from thingiverse.com/thing:4312) popped out.  I decided to experiment with a different kind of roller: instead of a sphere, I would use a cylinder capped by two 45 degree cones.  I figured this would print better on a makerbot; my spherical rollers ended up teardrop-shaped, and when they turned sideways they would get wedged in position.  The inner cavity of this bearing should theoretically prevent that, though in practice the tolerances here are way way too loose.  (As a side bonus, it's much easier to clean.)
I stole the the extend-o rod idea from  thingiverse.com/thing:5551 .
Future work: The hub ought to be tightened up and it has lots of excess plastic.  Also skeinforge35 doesn't handle it too well; when I print it the inner hub is hollow and has no bottom.  Luckily there's enough extra string floating around that it still works okay.

Instructions:
The hub and spokes are designed to be printed raftlessly. I had some curling problems with the extenders, so I rafted them. Print 1x mount, 1x hub, 4x spoke. This will get you out to a radius of 100mm. For another 80mm (which nicely holds the roll of filament that came with my Thingomatic), print a set of 4x extender. Cleaning the hub:
  • There's a miniature annular raft between the inner hub and outer hub; this helps the rollers get seated properly on their points. Cut or peel this away.
  • Take out your pocketknife and insert the blade into the annular hole at a 45 degree angle facing outwards. Run it around the outer perimiter of hole to cut all the strings.
  • Turn the knife 45 degrees inwards and run it around the inner perimeter of the annular hole.
  • Turn the hub over and do steps 2 and 3 again.
  • Wiggle your knife between each of the balls and pry them loose from each other.
  • Spinning the hub for a while (e.g. by chucking it into a drill) will make it turn more smoothly.
    • The 4 spokes should slide into the hub, with the optional extensions. If they need a little persuasion, tap them with a hammer. The mount replaces one of the extra two z-endstops on your Thing-o-Matic and hangs off the front. The hub's center square hole mates with the end of the mount. The holes in the mount may print out a bit small for your M3 bolts; if so drill them out. Once it's mounted, put the filament onto the spool and pull the loose end around until it's nice and tight. I taped my loose end to one of the spokes to keep everything neat, but this is probably not necessary.

title: simple filament spool stand for any width

description.text:
A simple construction concept to easily print out (without the need of any nuts or bolts) and to use it with any reel without having trouble on different widths.  
It is also printable in a short amount of time because of the clean design.  
Use standard (skate) bearing 608z. You can get them for a low price on Amazon or eBay.  
Enjoy!

Release notes [v 1.2] Mar 30, 2015
  • added stabilizer for better handling
  • added more options to setup guides to match different perimeters of spools
    • [v 1.1] Dec 7, 2014
  • added beam for more strength
  • changed base for better stand
  • added 2nd guide
  • changed position of 1st guide
  • changed width of the bearing mounts and base (-1 mm) for better fit
  • changed design and made it "curvy"
    • [v 1.0] Dec 3, 2014
  • initial submission

To get the whole construction you need... 2x filament_stand_base_2x.stl
4x filament_stand_guide_4x.stl I used red PLA @ 185°C and 40% infill without support (lay both objects on their back so they should print properly) It took about 1.5 hour for each "base" and about 3 minutes per "guide" You can print both objects with 100% size and they should fit perfect. I currently use it with 1 KG filament reels and it is stable enough to carry them. I don't know the limitations so keep an eye on that if you are planning to use it with more heavy reels.

UC4 is an enterprise automation package. We're hosting a UC4 user conference at work later this year, and I have a reputation around work as a patissier, so I wanted to make some UC4 rolled cookies (aka sugar cookies) I just noticed - the cookie cutter as printed looks backwards (it should be a mirror-image when upside down, of course) I think this might be a thingiverse bug, however - I don't recall having any issues the first time I printed this thing up, it was a few months ago however... You can check out UC4 and their great product at http://www.uc4.com/ If you happen to work for UC4, you should give my company a discount for all the free publicity I throw at you guys. Contact me privately if you'd like to take me up on that...

Print cookie cutter
Make a dough by mixing flour, water, eggs, butter, and sugar together according to your favorite recipe 
IMPORTANT!  Most amateurs skip this step - CHILL DOUGH FOR THIRTY MINUTES+
Roll out dough onto parchment paper
Flour cookie cutter liberally
Use cookie cutter to cut UC4 logo out of dough
Re-roll and re-cut left over dough (add a re-chill at the beginning if its getting too warm)
Don't move the cookies after cutting - they're a little fragile before baking.  Transfer the cookies already on the parchment paper directly to the baking sheet, instead.
Some recipes call for you to re-chill the cookies at this stage.  If your recipe includes this step, DO IT!!!
Bake cookies (according to usual recipe)
Use chocolate icing for the UC and either yellow sugar crystals or yellow colored icing for the 4.  The official color on the website is more of an orangeish color, but in the actual software it looks a little more orange-ish.
Or at least it used to before we installed version 8 - now the logo looks completely different LOLZ!
For those who aren't use to making cookies - the dough in cookies bakes as low as 115 degrees (just takes much longer) - so don't wait for them to be "done" before pulling them out!  Pull them out when they're a little underdone, and they'll finish baking AS THEY COOL - making for the perfectly done, moist cookie.

This bottle holder will let you anchor a row of cylindrical bottles for stacking in multiple layers - see photos for the application for wine.  It outputs files both for single color printing and for dualstrusion.  
This was originally designed for wine bottles, but should be customizable for any type of bottle - beer or soda, droppers, etc.

Instructions:
1) Measure the diameter of your bottles / the distance you want the bottles spaced.  Ideally you want them to be quite close together, although if there's variability between bottles (i.e. wine bottles) you might need a bit of clearance.
2) If you're planning on dualstruding, decide if you want all of the parts the same or if you want half of them with reversed colors vs. the other half.  You can use the "part" variable to preview each color.
3) Enter all of the parameters, including whether to mix dualstrusion, the bottle width, as well as your desired strip depth and thickness.  Depth should depend a bit on the size of the bottle - for big bottles like wine, you probably want two thin strips, one up front and one at the back.  For smaller bottles like a dropper, you can probably make one very deep strip.
4) Generate your STLs and get to printing!  Three files will be generated, one for solid color printing and two for dualstrusion.

This is a 1:10M scale of SRTM 90M elevation data with a 10x vertical exaggeration.  
This is way harder to do that it should be. I'll document it when I figure it out and get a decent printable model.

This is a rough outline of the steps used to create the file, mostly from the following guide: https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/11089897/3druckench/maps_to_3D.pdf Download 3DEM from http://freegeographytools.com/2009/3dem-website-is-gone-but-3dem-still-available-here Open 3DEM:
  • [File] -> [Load Terrain Model] -> GeoTiff DEM (tif) -> Load your geotiff (from the Thing files)
  • [File] -> [Save as USGS ASCII DEM] -> Save as USGS DEM File (*.dem)
    • Download AccuTrans3D from
    http://www.micromouse.ca/downloads.html
    Open AccuTrans3D:
  • [File] -> [Open DME as] -> [USGS 1-degree (ASCII) (*.dem)] -> Open file.
  • [Dem] -> [Convert to 3D (less water)]
    • Vertex Interval, “Pick - 10” (something less than 500k vertices).
    • Control Face Creation, “Drop Faces at Sea Level”
    • “OK”
  • [Tools_1] -> [Adjust Object (Mirror, Rotate, Scale, Translate)]
    • Scale -Position:
      -- x: 0.0001, y: 0.000141, z: 0.001
      -- [Scale]
      -- [Center on X and Y axis with Z at zero]
  • [Tools_1] -> [Extrude Pseudo 3D surface]
    • Thickness: 1
    • “Flat Bottom”
    • [Extrude]
    • “OK”
  • [Tools_1] -> [Adjust Object (Mirror, Rotate, Scale, Translate)]
    • Snap to Ground
    • X90
    • “OK”
  • [File] -> [Save As] -> [StereoLithography (ASCII)(*.stl)]

description.text: battery pack that allows you to have the 4batteries in a tight formation and then to extend that as a stick with as many more 4batteries ...

• print 2 pieces of battery_pack_end.stl
  • print as many batter_pack_middle.stl as you want
  • put m3 nuts into battery_pack_end (4 in each) and tighten with bolts
  • put batteries into one battery_pack_end
  • put battery_pack_middle over batteries
  • add more batteries if you like, and after each set add another battery_pack_middle .. make sure you slide battery_pack_middle to cover end of one and beginning of another set of 4 batteries
  • finally add second battery_pack_end
  • use the m3 threaded rod and thread it trough all plastic pieces, and tighten on each end with m3 nut
    • voila, you have your battery pack NOTE: The SCAD file have original battery dimensions! If your printer is not able to print holes that are accurate (visit stretch plugin in skeinforge) increase battery diameter in order to get holes where batteries will fit.

title: Printrbot Simple Metal Vertical Spool Holder

description.text:
UPDATE 5/12/2015: Now Customizable!
Thank you all for your feedback, many of you have said you wanted a taller version. Now you can open in Customizer and make it as tall as you need. Enjoy! :)

Yet another spool holder for the Printrbot Simple Metal in a vertical configuration, in which the filament line gracefully descends from the spool to the extruder.  
This is a two piece design consisting of a base and an arm. The hole in the base is angled 5 degrees to compensate for the leveraged weight of a spool so that the arm remains somewhat level under load.   
The length and height position of the arm works for the various small and large hole spools, and the new Makerbot large diameter flat reel.

Print these pieces with medium or higher density since they both will be bearing the force of the weight of a spool. Recommend that the pieces cool completely before they are put into use, otherwise a deformation may occur while they are still warm.  Support is not necessary nor recommended.  
The base is easy to install if you first fit each hole separately. Make sure that the thicker part of the base slot is in the same direction as the arm because of the leaning design. The arm should tilt upwards when empty, and be nominally level when holding a full spool. OpenSCAD code is included if you need to adjust anything.
